    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>CANADA TRADE SETBACKS</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Elizabeth Olson</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Olson, Elizabeth</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>World Trade Organization deals Canada two losses, with ruling against country's handling of certain patents and another ruling in favor of France's ban of Canadian building-product exports containing asbestos; WTO upholds earlier ruling that Canadian law limiting some patent protection to 17 years, instead of 20, violated global trade rules; decision primarily affects pharmaceutical patents; in asbestos case, WTO publishes official ruling allowing France's ban on grounds it was justified by exceptions for protecting human health (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>The World Trade Organization dealt Canada two losses, with a ruling against the country's handling of certain patents and another ruling in favor of France's ban of Canadian building-product exports containing asbestos. A W.T.O. panel upheld an earlier ruling that a Canadian law limiting some patent protection to 17 years, instead of 20, violated global trade rules. The decision primarily affects pharmaceutical patents. In the asbestos case, the W.T.O. published the official ruling allowing France's ban, even though such prohibitions are usually not permitted, on grounds it was justified by exceptions for protecting human health.</p>
        <p>Elizabeth Olson</p>
      </block>
